value.value: A small silk gland with globular lumen and short duct, discharging in a spigot on a posterior median or lateral spinneret.
A large silk gland with tubular elongate lumen, discharging in a spigot on a posterior median or posterior lateral spinneret of an adult female.
A large silk gland with complex lumen and long duct, discharging in a spigot on a posterior lateral spinneret.

definition.value: Flagelliform glands are defined for ecribellate spiders only, and are probably homologous to the pseudoflagelliform glands of cribellate spiders.

value.value: A large silk gland with complex ramidied lumen, discharging in a spigot on a posterior lateral spinneret.
A short seta with raised base on the prolateral basal surface of the palpal femur, most often used for stridulation against opposing ridges on the chelicerae.

A specialized seta at the tip of the tarsus, below the claws, with a ventral serrate side. They occur in araneoids, austrochilids, and other araneomorphs, and interact with the inferior claw to grasp a silk thread.

A sensory organ is a cluster of cells. It is part of a nervous system and consists of receptor cells, which form a multicellular unit that may include accessory cells, which serve as supportive structures, stimulus guiding structures or protective structures.
An outgrow of the body with articles and muscles.
A hook-like extension of the superior claws, grasping the folded base of a claw tuft seta. The clasper may be in one piece or composed by several claw teeth appressed together.
A comb of setae at the ventral tip of metatarsus III and IV.
A cusple on the ventral surface of a leg.
The tarsal organ of the female palpal tarsus.
The tarsal organ on the leg tarsus.
A mature individual, with fully developed sexual organs.
Anatomical system that consists of muscles, tendons and apodemes.
The portion of tissue that is composed of contractile fibers.
A thin extension of cuticular tubes lined with epithelium, where a muscle inserts.
A section of an appendage, delimited from another article, or from its insertion on the body, by joints.
The anatomical cluster that makes a flexible articulation between articles of appendages, or their insertion on the body.
The joint that is operated by muscles that insert on the rim of the distal article. Eudesmatic joints delimit podomeres.
The joint that is operated by muscles that do not insert on the rim of the distal article. Adesmatic joints delimit pseudopodomeres.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of the chelicerae, labrum, labium, palpal coxae, and conjunctivae connecting them.
Anatomical entity that has mass.
Material anatomical entity that has inherent 3D shape and is generated by coordinated expression of the organism's own genome.

Anatomical structure consisting of at least two non-overlapping organs, multi-tissue aggregates or portion of tissues or cells of different types that does not constitute an organism, organ, multi-tissue aggregate, or portion of tissue.
Anatomical group that has its parts adjacent to one another.
Anatomical group that has as its parts distinct anatomical structures interconnected by anatomical structures at a lower level of granularity.
The anatomical cluster that is composed of epithelial cell(s) that secrete or excrete materials not related to their ordinary metabolic needs.
A gland that discharges its secretion into the spermophor.
A gland on the copulatory bulb, not connected to the spermophor, that may be involved in the production of the mating plug.

definition.value: Found in Micaria sociabilis (Sentenska et al., in press) and Amaurobius (Suhm et al. 1996).

value.value: A cuticular structure made of a file and a plectrum, that produce acoustic or seismic vibrations.

One of the repeated divisions of the whole organism along the antero-posterior axis. The anatomical cluster that is connected to other segments via conjunctivae and muscles and is delimited by its sclerites.
Anatomical structure which is a primary subdivision of whole organism. The mereological sum of these is the whole organism.
Anatomical structure, that consists of similar cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships.
Anatomical entity that has no mass.

Non-material anatomical entity of three dimensions, that is generated by morphogenetic or other physiologic processes; is surrounded by one or more anatomical structures; contains one or more organism substances or anatomical structures.
A wide space between chelicerae and endites.
A conical, sclerotized process on the promargin or retromargin of the chelicerae, sometimes also on the cheliceral furrow, as denticles.
A process on the mesal surface of the paturon, often keel shaped, extending distally, often meeting the fang tip to form a chela.
A cluster of thick macrosetae, sometimes located on a process, placed anteriorly near the base of the fang.
The muscle that originates on the dorsal part of the palpal tarsus and attaches through a tendon on the basal part of the copulatory bulb.

The muscle that originates in the palpal tibia and attaches through a tendon winding on the basal part of the copulatory bulb, or enters the bulb and attaches to the spermophore (in some Synspermiata).
The duct connecting the sperm storage site in the female genitalia with the uterus externus or posterior diverticulum.
A duct in the female genitalia connecting the copulatory opening to the sperm storage site.
A large, elaborate process on the retrolateral side of cymbium.

definition.value: The procursus is a synapomorphy of Pholcidae (Huber 2000).

value.value: A process on the distal end of the distal sclerotized tube or radix.
A sclerite connecting the embolus with the radix, and containing the spermophor.

definition.value: The stipes can be simply either a subdivision of the radix or the enlarged base of the embolus (Coddington 1990).

value.value: A sclerite of the copulatory bulb arising from the tegulum, in addition to the median apophysis.
A depression often associated with glands, near the ocular area.
A large silk gland with elongate lumen and long duct, discharging in a spigot on a posterior median spinneret.
